The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                A man and a woman involved in an extramarital affair were awarded life imprisonment on Monday for murdering Howrah homemaker Srabonti Ghosh and her nine-year-old daughter Prapti. Samir Barik, 36, and Somashree Das, 32, will also have to pay a fine of Rs 5,000 each for the crime committed on February 26, 2008, failing which their jail term will be increased by six months. Besides, the Howrah district and sessions court sentenced Samir to an additional two years rigorous imprisonment for stealing Srabontis jewellery after the murder.  olice said Samir, a resident of Duttapukur in North 24-Parganas, and Somashree, a neighbour of Srabonti in Jagachha, were having an illicit affair. They used to meet in Srabontis house where the 35-year-old homemaker took some pictures of the duo in a compromising position. The two told the police during interrogation that they had decided to kill Srabonti when she threatened to expose them.  rabontis throat was slit with a bonti while Prapti, who witnessed the crime, was strangled with a towel.     Two siblings were found floating in a pond near their home in Gouranganagar in the New Town police station area on Monday afternoon. Police said Suvodip Halder, 7, and Koyel, 8, had gone to take a bath in the pond. Their mother Sikha went looking for them with neighbours and found their bodies in the pond. The bodies have been sent for post-mortem.     Truck driver Bapi Mondal and his help who is yet to be identified were killed after their vehicle met with an accident on the Jagulia-Bongaon Road and Kalyani-Barrackpore Highway crossing early on Monday. Police said the truck had collided with an overloaded trailer. The driver of the trailer fled leaving behind his vehicle.    An inspection team comprising members of the police, CESC, the directorate of electricity, civic body and the fire services department visited Poddar Court and Teriti Bazar on Rabindra Sarani on Monday. The team had suggested certain fire-safety measures after the Nandram fire in 2008. A CESC official said the wiring at Poddar Court had been improved and one of the two oil transformers had been converted to a dry-type transformer. At Teriti Bazaar, only 50 per cent of the suggestions had been implemented, the official said.    A number of shops in a market at Lake Gardens were gutted in a fire early on Monday. Firemen said the blaze started around 3am and four tenders took three hours to douse the flames. No one was injured. The extent of damage and the cause of the fire are yet to be ascertained.     Low-cost carrier SpiceJet is set to increase the number of flights from Calcutta to Mumbai and Guwahati (via Agartala), from May 10, a spokesperson for the airline said. SpiceJet had started daily flights between Calcutta and Agartala on April 15.     Seventeen supporters of the Burrabazar District Chhatra Parishad were arrested on Monday for demonstrating in front of Writers Buildings against power cuts, price rise and alleged terrorism by the CPM and SFI.             
